    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad opened a station in Johnsonburg in 1911, linking the village to Hoboken and Buffalo.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnsonburg%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Johnsonburg’s historic district, added to the National Register in 1992, showcases 19th‑century architecture and the village’s linear layout.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4,
        28
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia",
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnsonburg%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "In the early 1800s, Johnsonburg boasted a post office, tavern, church, school, tannery, and several artisan shops, making it a local hub.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.livingplaces.com/NJ/Warren_County/Frelinghuysen_Township/Johnsonburg_Historic_District.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Although bypassed by later transportation booms, Johnsonburg’s buildings have survived largely unchanged, preserving its distinctive rural character.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
